        narration: "Cravings feel overwhelming, but neuroscience tells us they are time-limited. Most cravings peak at around 15 to 20 minutes and then begin to subside, even without using any substance. The challenge is surviving that peak. A targeted yoga sequence gives your body something to do and your mind something to focus on during those critical minutes. Balance poses like Tree Pose are especially effective because they demand complete attention — you literally cannot think about using while trying not to fall over. Legs Up the Wall, a gentle inversion, changes the blood flow to your brain and activates the baroreceptors in your neck, which signal your heart to slow down. This is the same reflex that makes splashing cold water on your face calming. Hip-opening poses like Pigeon Pose can release tension held in the psoas muscle, which connects directly to the diaphragm and is involved in the fight-or-flight response. By releasing this tension, you reduce the physical component of craving.",
        exercise: "Create a personal 15-minute craving emergency yoga sequence using the poses discussed. Write it on an index card and keep it accessible. Practice it twice this week even when you are not craving, so the sequence becomes automatic. The sequence should include: one minute of breath work, a balance pose, a standing pose, a hip opener, and a closing inversion.",
