        narration: "Exercise is a powerful emotional regulation tool, but like any tool, it works best when used strategically. Different types of exercise affect mood differently. Vigorous aerobic exercise — where your heart rate is elevated to 70 to 85 percent of your maximum — triggers the release of endorphins and endocannabinoids that reduce anxiety for several hours after the workout. This is why a hard run can feel like hitting a reset button on a stressful day. However, vigorous exercise is not appropriate for every emotional state. When you are overwhelmed with grief, anger, or trauma-related distress, your nervous system is already in overdrive. Pushing into high-intensity exercise can actually amplify distress. In these moments, low-intensity movement like walking or gentle stretching allows your body to process the emotion without adding more activation. Rhythm-based movement, such as swimming or cycling at a steady pace, can be particularly soothing because the repetitive pattern helps regulate the nervous system. The important thing is to develop your own emotional map of movement — learning through experience which types of exercise help you with which emotional states.",
        exercise: "Create an Exercise-Emotion Map. Draw a grid with emotions on one axis (anxiety, anger, sadness, restlessness, low motivation, craving) and exercise types on the other (vigorous cardio, walking, stretching, strength training, dance/rhythm). Over the next two weeks, experiment with different combinations and rate effectiveness 1-5. This personalized map becomes your emotional regulation toolkit.",
        duration: "20 min"
