        narration: "The research on exercise adherence tells us something humbling: about 50 percent of people who start an exercise program quit within six months. In recovery, we know a lot about what makes behavior change stick, and the principles apply directly to movement. The most important factor is not the perfect program — it is your identity. When you shift from 'I am trying to exercise more' to 'I am a person who moves every day,' you have crossed a threshold. Every time you move, you are casting a vote for that identity. Research from the University of British Columbia found that the single strongest predictor of long-term exercise adherence was exercising with others. This makes perfect sense in recovery, where connection is already a core healing mechanism. A walking group, a recreational sports league, or even a regular gym time with a sober friend doubles the benefits. Finally, plan for setbacks now, while your motivation is high. Write down exactly what you will do when you miss a day, a week, or a month. Having a restart protocol prevents a lapse from becoming a collapse.",
