        narration: "Strength training and addiction recovery share a fundamental philosophy: progressive overload. In the gym, you start with a weight that challenges you, and when it becomes manageable, you add a little more. In recovery, you face one day, one challenge, one trigger at a time, and each success makes you more capable. This parallel is not coincidental — both processes involve neuroplasticity, the brain's ability to rewire itself through repeated experience. When you train with weights, your body releases a cascade of beneficial hormones. Testosterone and growth hormone, which support muscle repair, mood regulation, and cognitive function, are produced at elevated levels for 24 to 48 hours after a training session. For people in recovery, whose endocrine systems may have been disrupted by substance use, this is genuinely therapeutic. A 2018 meta-analysis in JAMA Psychiatry reviewed 33 randomized controlled trials and concluded that resistance training significantly reduced depressive symptoms regardless of health status, training volume, or degree of strength gains. The mental health benefits were independent of whether people actually got physically stronger.",
        exercise: "Set three strength training goals: one for 4 weeks, one for 10 weeks, and one for 6 months. Make them specific and measurable (e.g., 'hold a 60-second plank' or 'perform 10 full push-ups'). Write each goal on an index card and post them where you will see them daily. Below each goal, write why it matters to your recovery.",
