        narration: "Your first month of strength training is about building habits and mastering movement patterns, not testing limits. The good news is that beginners make the fastest progress. In the first six to eight weeks, you will get noticeably stronger — not because your muscles are growing significantly yet, but because your nervous system is learning to recruit muscle fibers more efficiently. This neural adaptation phase is deeply satisfying because progress is rapid and consistent. Your program should include two to three full-body sessions per week, never on consecutive days. Each session should cover all six movement patterns with one exercise each. Aim for 2 to 3 sets of 8 to 12 repetitions per exercise, at a difficulty where the last 2 reps of each set feel challenging but doable. This is called Rate of Perceived Exertion, or RPE, and you want to be at about a 6 or 7 out of 10. Record every session in a training log: exercises, weights, sets, reps, and how you felt. This log serves the same function as a recovery journal — it provides evidence of your progress when motivation wanes.",
        exercise: "Complete your first full-body training session: Goblet Squat or Chair Squat 3x10, Hip Hinge with light weight 3x10, Push-Up (modified as needed) 3x8, Band Row 3x10, Farmer's Carry 3x30 seconds, Plank 3x20 seconds. Rest 60-90 seconds between sets. Record all weights and reps in your training log. Rate your overall session difficulty 1-10.",
