        narration: "After your first three to six months of consistent training, the rapid beginner gains will slow. This is normal — it does not mean the training has stopped working. It means your body has adapted to the current stimulus and needs new challenges. This is where intermediate programming concepts become valuable. Periodization is the practice of systematically varying your training over time. A simple approach is to alternate between phases: four weeks of higher reps with moderate weight for muscle building, followed by four weeks of lower reps with heavier weight for strength. Every fourth or fifth week, take a deload — reduce your weights by 40 to 50 percent and focus on perfect form. This might feel like a waste, but deloads allow accumulated fatigue to clear and actually prime your body for the next wave of progress. Think of strength training as a decades-long practice, not a short-term program. Just as your recovery deepens and evolves over years, your training will mature from basic movements to more sophisticated programming. The person you are in the gym in five years will be different from who you are today, and that evolution itself is part of the recovery journey.",
        exercise: "Design a 12-week intermediate program outline with three phases: Phase 1 (weeks 1-4) hypertrophy focus at 3x10-12, Phase 2 (weeks 5-8) strength focus at 4x6-8, Phase 3 (weeks 9-12) mixed with a deload in week 12. Choose exercises for each phase that cover all six movement patterns. Set a specific strength goal for week 12 and write down why achieving it matters to your recovery.",
